Abstract unscramble 
Zebrafish are useful vertebrates in which to carry out large-scale
mutagenic screens to identify developmentally important genes. 
In order to follow the development of the zebrafish immune system,
we previously isolated and characterized the recombination activating 
genes, rag1 and rag2. 
This paper describes the cloning and characterization of another
such marker, ika1, which encodes a zinc finger transcription factor
necessary for early lymphocyte differentiation. 
Whole mount in situ hybridization revealed expression of ika1 in 24 hr
embryos in the intermediate cell mass, the first site of hematopoiesis 
(Weinstein et al., 1996), and the head. 
We also report the continuing efforts to create transgenes with the 
green fluorescent protein-coding region under the control of the 
promoters of rag1 and ika1. 
Fish containing these transgenes could then be mutagenized and 
screened quickly and easily for mutations in the immune system. 

